                    WINGS FFXI PRIVATE SERVER LICENSE
                      Version 1.2, 14 January 2021

 Copyright (C) 2020-2021 the Wings project.

                                Preamble

  The Wings License governs your usage or distribution of Wings, a code
base that attempts to emulate an online server for the online video game
Final Fantasy XI (Copyright Square Enix, Co.) as it was in the beginning
of 2010, after the Wings of the Goddess expansion pack has been released.

  This license is a modified version of the Project Topaz license, which
is itself (c) Project Topaz, used under the assumption that the Project
Topaz license is subject to itself. Should we be notified otherwise by
the copyright author of the Topaz License we will reword the license as
needed but the meaning will remain the same.

  The Wings project is based on project Topaz, which is itself based on the
earlier, now-defunct Darkstar Project, which is licensed under the GNU
GPL version 2 or greater (at the user's choice). While under the terms of
the GNU GPL, distribution of the server, either verbatim or modified,
require the distribution of the source code under the same license, network
usage does not count as distribution. This means that server operators
may enhance and build upon the project without sharing their enhancements
back with the community or the players playing on their server as long as
they do not distribute the server binaries or scripts.

  We feel that lacking this requirement ultimately harms the broader community 
of developers who work on server emulators. Some server operators choose to 
"compete" with other operators by taking the code base we all share, making 
proprietary modifications to emulate additional features which currently do
not exist in the shared code base, and then not share those features back
with the community of developers.

  This behavior leads to the community constantly "re-inventing the wheel",
spending time that could have otherwise been spent developing entirely new
features for the project in advance of our common goals. It also disheartens
developers who would share their modifications with the community, but 
feel discouraged when their code is taken by a server operator, modified
with additional improvements, but kept privately as an "edge" over others,
including the original developer of the feature.

  For these reasons, The Wings Project instead intends to be licensed primarily 
under the terms of the GNU Affero General Public License Version 3, which 
stipulates that use of a Program over a network qualifies as distribution, 
and that the source code of the modified Program needs to be offered to
users interacting with the Program.

  The Wings project includes code originating from both the Darkstar project
and project topaz. Code originating from the Darkstar project is licensed
under the GNU GPL version 2 or greater and cannot be relicensed, however as
Wings uses the Darkstar code, we choose to use it under the terms of the GNU
GPL version 3. Section 13 of the GNU GPLv3 permits the combination of code
under that license with code under the license of the GNU AGPLv3, which itself
has a similar counterpart exemption.

  The Topaz project uses a modified version of the GNU AGPLv3, which permit
the modification of the code without distribution as long as the said
modification is a "customized experience", i.e. producing a behavior which
is intentionally different than the behavior of the retail game.

  This license states which of the licenses pertain to which parts of this
combined source code. 

  The precise terms and conditions for using, copying, distribution and
modification of the Wings project follow.

                       TERMS AND CONDITIONS

  0. Definitions.

  "This License" refers to version 1 of the Wings Project License Agreement.

  "GNU GPLv3", "GPLv3", and "GPL" refer to version 3 of the GNU General
Public License. A copy should have been included in the source code you  
have received in a file named "GPL3". If not, you may find a copy online 
at <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.

  "GNU AGPLv3", "AGPLv3", and "AGPL" refer to version 3 of the GNU Affero 
General Public License. A copy should have been included in the source code 
you have received in a file named "AGPL3". If not, you may find a copy 
online at <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.

  "Project Topaz License" refers to the license of Project Topaz. A copy
should have been included in the source code you have received in a file
named "TOPAZLICENSE". If not, you may find a copy online at
<https://github.com/project-topaz/topaz/blob/release/LICENSE>.

  The terms "Copyright", "Program", "modify", and "convey" are as defined 
in version 3 of the GNU General Public License.

  "Source code" is as defined in version 3 of the GNU General Public License.

  "Commit" refers to modifications to the Program which are packaged, 
transmitted, and patched into the source code as "Git Commits" utilizing 
the Git distributed version control system. A commit being governed by 
a license means all source code and modifications within that commit 
package are subject to that license.

  "Private server" refers to a computer or network system running any instance 
of the Wings project, in whole or in part, which accepts connections or commands 
from users other than one physically present at the computer system. 
Computer or network systems which pass or forward commands to any instance
of the Wings project considered part of the same private server, regardless 
of how the Wings project instances or computer systems are physically distributed.

  "Player interface" means an interface that a user connecting to a 
private server visibly sees on a computer screen, which can relay text, 
that a user is capable of reading or viewing the text history of from 
within the same interface.

  1. Project Repository.

  The Wings Project is an open source project, which accepts
contributions from many developers all over the world. It utilizes 
Git, a distributed version control system, for its development. 
The current source code for the project is available online at: 
<https://www.gitlab.com/ffxiwings/wings/>

  As part of using Git, code contributions by developers can be 
be tracked and attributed on an individual level. If you 
obtained this source code by cloning it from GitLab, you can use 
any number of Git clients found online to parse this information.

  If instead you obtained this source code by downloading it 
without cloning, or were given it by a third party, and the archive 
you received lacks this Git information, you can and are encouraged 
to view this information on our GitLab repository.

