  All Git commits which originate from Project Topaz, either before
or after the Wings project's initial repository commit, are governed
by the Topaz license. Under that license, any source code files which
are not clearly marked as being governed by the AGPLv3 may be assumed
to be governed by the GPLv3.

  All Git commits which originate from the Wings project itself are
governed by the AGPLv3 without any further terms under section 7 of
the license other than those specified in section 3 of this license,
unless explicitly stated otherwise.

  Contributors of the Wings project may choose to dual-license their
work, in which case you are entitled to use those specific portions
under either the contributor's license or the GNU AGPLv3. Such dual
licensed code will be clearly marked. If no such mark exists, the code
is assumed to be governed by the GNU AGPLv3 alone.

  Your rights to use, modify, and distribute source code are governed 
by the license which the original work was licensed under. However, 
per Section 13 of both the GPLv3 and the AGPLv3, all modifications 
you make to this Program, or works you combine with this Program, 
are subject to the requirements of the AGPLv3 concerning interaction 
through a network.

  3. Additional Terms.

  Through Section 7, Additional Terms of the AGPLv3, we are adding
the following additional terms to our material:

    a) ATTRIBUTION.
    If you convey this Program to a recipient, you must preserve 
    and also convey to the recipient any existing lists of 
    Program authors and contributors, such as those displayed by 
    the Program, or those found in an AUTHORS file. All existing 
    dates, and all existing copyright notices must also be retained.
    
    As an exception to the above, you may alter any attributions 
    or notices added by the Wings project to the extent required to 
    remedy known factual inaccuracies.

    If you modify and convey this Program, you are permitted to 
    to add yourself to such lists. You are also permitted to
    rename any attribution files, so long as the filename still 
    clearly indicates that the authors listed in the file 
    contributed to the modified Program. If this is done, you must 
    include a notice in any new author attribution files you 
    create stating the following:
    "Contributors to the Wings project, upon which this Program is based, 
     can be found: " followed by the path to original file.

    b) MISREPRESENTATION.
    The origin of this Program must not be misrepresented. You
    shall not claim, suggest, nor imply you wrote this Program, 
    in whole or in part, unless you are the original author for 
    the distinct part for which you claim to be the author.

    If you convey modified versions of this Program, you may not 
    misrepresent that modified Program as being "The Wings project", 
    unless that modified Program is being conveyed back to the
    Wings project with the intention of the modification's inclusion 
    into the project.
    
    If you convey modified versions to recipients other than the Wings 
    project, you shall mark the material such that any users interacting 
    with the Program are given notice - through an applicable player 
    interface of your choosing - that the Program has been modified 
    from its original version, unless that modification was necessary 
    for the basic operation of the server.
    
  4. Special exceptions.
  
    As a special exception, the copyright holders grant you permission to
    withhold publication of specific commits for a period of 14 days at
    most for the following reasons:
    
    a) In case of an out of band commit to a running server in order to
    solve an urgent issue, where going through the proper commit procedure
    is not possible.
    
    b) In case the commit is a patch to an exploit, where a public
    disclosure delay is required in order to allow time for server owners
    (whether based on Wings or not) to patch their servers before the
    information goes public.
    
    c) In case there is a need to debug the commit in a multi-player
    environment.
    
    For the purpose of this exception the 14-day count begins when such
    code begins running on a public facing server for the fist time.

  5. Revised Versions.

  Should a new version of the GNU AGPL license be issued, you are allowed
to use the code under the terms of the new version as long as it has
sections equivalent to Section 7 and Section 13 of the GNU GPLv3 and the
GNU AGPLv3 in order to combine the work with code originating from the
Darkstar project and Project Topaz.

  The Wings project may publish new or revised versions of this license. 
These new versions will be similar in spirit, but may differ to address 
new problems or concerns with the project by modifying the additional
permissions we grant to you, or modify the restrictions imposed on you,  
to the extent allowed under AGPLv3 Section 7, Additional Terms.

  The license for which you may use the Program is the one you 
received along with a copy of this source code, or at your option, 
any later version of the Wings project License Agreement that has 
been published by the Wings project. However, no additional obligations 
are imposed upon authors or copyright holders due to your choice 
in following a later version of this license.
